 ==General election==
 No Republican received the requisite 250 write-in votes in the Republican primary to become that party's nominee, but Peduto received 228 write-ins, Darlene Harris received 229, and John Welch received 65, with 21 votes that had not been verified.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Slaby|first1=M.J.|title=No, Darlene Harris can’t run for Pittsburgh mayor as a Republican|url=https://theincline.com/2017/06/05/no-darlene-harris-cant-run-for-pittsburgh-mayor-as-a-republican/|publisher=The Incline|access-date=8 June 2017}}</ref> Two [[Independent politician|independent]] candidates—James Rack and Khalid Raheem—filed to appear on the ballot before the early August 2017 deadline, but were removed from the ballot in late August after their nominating petitions were successfully challenged by the Allegheny County Democratic Party. Rack had failed to provide a financial interest statement to the city clerk and Raheem's petition contained too few city resident signatures to qualify.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Potter|first1=Chris|title=Two mayoral challengers removed from ballot|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/local/city/2017/08/29/mayor-pittsburgh-Independent-challengers-removed-ballot-James-Rack-Khalid-Raheem/stories/201708290201|access-date=8 November 2017|publisher=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|date=29 August 2017}}</ref> Ultimately, Peduto was re-elected, having been the only candidate listed on the general election ballot.<ref name=results/>

